<@1360003496384008262>  I created the Inner Circle inside a regular chat. It all started with the idea of building a kind of journal-meets-diary, where I could write or speak about whatever I‚Äôm thinking ‚Äî and then the Inner Circle would respond.

It‚Äôs made up of different AI experts, each focused on a topic that interests me, and they each give their own perspective or feedback based on what I share.

Now, after several weeks of using it, I‚Äôm considering moving it to Custom GPT, which is supposed to offer more flexibility. But honestly, the regular chat has worked really well so far ‚Äî especially because I set it up to remember previous conversations, so the Inner Circle has context and can give more informed responses.

If you‚Äôre interested, we could totally set up a call sometime to talk about it in more depth ‚Äî I‚Äôd love to share and hear your thoughts too!
How are you building the Inner Circle? Through Custom GPTs or something else?
Sounds like I need to give vibe dialoguing a try! Love that term!

Oh wow <@992174053882331240> , I've been building advisors through Custom GPTs but more on the Buddhism, mindfulness and investing side! I've got a faux Warren Buffett, etc. And I just read the Dao De Jing a few months back. I think I've been pretty attached to my vision so when Chat GPT gives me things that aren't quite what I want I go into "editing" mode rather than trying to take it in at the higher level and letting what it created inspire new directions or help me ask better questions about why I was trying to do something in the first place... Definitely great food for thought

Hey <@1360003496384008262> , totally agree ‚Äî that part really stuck with me too. What resonated most was how Rick treats not knowing as a strength, not a weakness. That really mirrors the process I‚Äôve been exploring with my Inner Circle project ‚Äî where I use AI advisors built around Taoism, Jungian archetypes, and introspective frameworks.
It also reminded me of how I approach MidJourney prompts. I‚Äôve been experimenting with something I call ‚Äúdirty prompting‚Äù ‚Äî where I intentionally leave space in the prompt for the AI to surprise me. I don‚Äôt try to control every variable. Instead, I let the model improvise, and often what comes back is more poetic, strange, or alive. It‚Äôs the same vibe Rick was talking about: co-creating with uncertainty, letting go of the illusion of full authorship.
Vibe coding, for me, feels more like vibe dialoguing ‚Äî co-writing with the unknown. And I love that he brought the Dao De Jing into the mix‚Ä¶ made me feel less alone in trying to merge code with consciousness

I listened to this just yesterday, so good! Loved when he talked about how vibe coding is like making art because when you create you know that you don't know what you're doing. Plus the part of about, when the LLM gives you back not what you asked for but a variation, being open to riff from there rather than staying married to your vision of it. <@992174053882331240> What did you get out of it?

Hy @everyone , just wanted to share this interview, I found intersting, Headline: Rick Rubin on Art, Life, and Vibe Coding
 Source / Date: AI Daily Brief ‚Äì YouTube Interview, May 2025
üîó Link: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6BDsFUvPqI0

- Who is Rick Rubin?
Rick Rubin is one of the most influential music producers of the last 40 years ‚Äî known for his minimalist, intuition-led style. He‚Äôs worked across nearly every genre with artists like Johnny Cash, Beastie Boys, System of a Down, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Jay-Z, and Adele. Rubin is a creative philosopher at heart, more monk than manager ‚Äî a producer who doesn't play instruments, but knows how to listen like few others.

- Quick Summary:
In this rich conversation, Rubin reflects on how a meme turned him into the accidental mascot of vibe coding ‚Äî a term now linked to his new project The Way of Code, co-created with Anthropic's Claude AI. The work merges generative code, poetic meditation, and the timeless wisdom of the Dao De Jing.

- He explores:

How AI can't replicate the artist's evolving point of view

Why letting go is key to authentic creativity

The role of mistakes and emergence in making something meaningful

How AI can become a creative partner, not a machine of control

-Takeaway:
Creativity isn‚Äôt about mastery ‚Äî it‚Äôs about attunement to the unknown. You don‚Äôt control it. You collaborate with it.

-Why this resonated with me:
I‚Äôd already been developing a personal project called The Inner Circle ‚Äî a group of AI advisors shaped by Taoism, Jungian psychology, and Musashi‚Äôs Dokk≈çd≈ç.
But it was Andrea Hickethier‚Äôs PEACH system that lit the fuse ‚Äî her framework helped me translate introspection into interface, and sketch a system where AI becomes a council of reflection.

Listening to Rick Rubin wasn‚Äôt what sparked the idea ‚Äî it simply felt like I was hearing someone describe, in his language, what I had already begun to build.

‚ú® Sometimes, resonance isn‚Äôt inspiration. It‚Äôs recognition.
